Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Chop the @potatoes{700%g} lengthways into 1cm slices, then chop into 1cm wide fries (no need to peel).

Pop the fries onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, bake on the top shelf until golden, ~{30-35%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, remove the @slow cooked British chicken{290%g} from its packaging and place in an #ovenproof dish{}, discarding the juices.

Roast on the middle shelf of your oven for ~{20-25%minutes}.

In the meantime, trim the @carrot{1}(trimmed), then coarsely grate (no need to peel). Trim and thinly slice the @spring onion{2}(trimmed and thinly sliced).

In a #medium bowl{}, combine the carrot, spring onion, @rice vinegar{15%ml}, @sambal paste{15%g} (add less if you prefer things milder) and @sugar{1%tsp}.

> See pantry for sambal amount.

Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then set your 'kimchi' aside.

Grate the @mature cheddar cheese{60%g}.

Cut the @lime{1} into wedges.

Crush the @salted peanuts{25%g} in the unopened sachet using a #rolling pin{}.

Once the chicken is cooked, remove from the oven, then use two #forks{} to shred the chicken as finely as you can.

> IMPORTANT: Ensure the chicken is piping hot throughout.

Stir through the @gochujang paste{100%g}, @honey{30%g} and a squeeze of lime juice from a lime wedge.

> TIP: If your honey has hardened, pop it in a bowl of hot water for 1 min.

When everything's ready, share the fries between your plates. Top with the gochujang chicken and serve the 'kimchi' alongside.

Sprinkle the cheese and peanuts over the loaded fries to finish.

Serve with any remaining lime wedges for squeezing over.

Enjoy!